Your art is like a mirror, it is you but in a different form…

Art allows us a way to process our inner most self: what do we think and feel? what do we value? what questions are we asking? Art is an expression of feeling… one that will live on well after the artist and the original collector. It is personal, distinctive, unique - this is what makes art so valuable, and what makes it suitable for the collector who purchases it. 

Art pulls out from you something greater than the mundane of life… beauty, whether you are the one making it or the one viewing/experiencing it. Art allows for an expression of feeling and beauty that otherwise may not have ever been expressed, in that way, in that moment, in time. Never create from less than that feeling, never purchase for less than that feeling! ❤️CF #art #feeling

Nourish and water all that is around you. Bring out the best in everything surrounding you. Maximize the potential of something in your presence. Make the thing in your presence the most beautiful it could be. Yes, every detail counts.

I visited a client’s home in Meaford, Ontario this past summer, with the intention to conceive something distinctive for the space. I wanted to bring this breathtaking view of Georgian Bay just a little bit closer to home…☝🏼this was the result 🖼️🌊. ‘Healing Horizons’ 36” x 54” oil on aluminum composite. 

I’ve always been astounded by beauty, the beauty of our earth, of people, places, music, art, fashion, words etc. Beauty speaks meaning to people. It can be challenging to make something beautiful but if you can make just one thing in your life beautiful then you’ve established a relationship with beauty. It can then ripple out and affect others in ways you cannot begin to imagine. That’s really an invitation to something much greater than ourselves. 

On my 🎨 an array of blues; ultramarine, indigo, phthalo, cobalt with hints of viridian, magenta and orange.

🏠 Home of the lovely @kristijanarakic @drkguidingwellness ❤️

Wow! A trip down memory lane… I just received this memory notification on my phone, from February 22, 2011. This was my graduating thesis exhibit from my undergrad, the body of work is titled “Candy Coated.” What great memories, with such talented artists. I never thought I would be here today, still as an artist, looking back on these moments. I remember, as if it was yesterday, my grandfather looking at me with such pride and telling me never to quit creating art. He was a great artist himself, I hope he’d be proud of me today ❤️. These works sold out that summer at the Toronto Outdoor Art Exhibition. 

An artist’s work is always a reflection of where they are in their life at that time. I have been modelling since I was a child, and fashion was always predominant in my life and work. I had also been spending my summers living in Italy and that’s when my love for Renaissance realism exploded… my work became much more lifelike, the brushwork more tight and meticulous. 

“Candy Coated”. Inspired by the world of fashion, this work explores the themes of sensuality and sexuality, as expressed through lips (one of the most visible human sensory organs). Lips speak a thousand words without having to utter a sound. This work encompasses, a wide range of both positive and negative representations of fashion, consumerism and beauty. 

#memorylane #rememberhowfaryouvecome

Beauty is in the details, and perception is everything. It seems like one large mass of blue water but in reality there are so many facets of detail and color (as seen on my mini palette). Every glisten is surrounded by an aura of color. If you haven’t noticed, I am obsessed with details… it’s not that I’m looking to create perfection, I simply find peace in the creative process, I like to take my time with my art. Today, much of everything is made quickly, and also thrown away quickly. I’m not interested in contributing to that energy. I’m interested in quality, dedication, devotion, and the exquisite care of execution. Every detail is as important as the whole, every brushstroke, a tribute to something deeper than us. ✨ 

❤️CF | @artistcarina 🌊

Can you relate to saying goodbye to your art?.. knowing that a piece of you goes with it. How beautiful! 

Images 1, 2 & 3
Last week we crated up this big girl behind me and shipped her off to California. Thanks to photographer/videographer Dave Morgado @itsyoboynorte for documenting this final goodbye with “Il soffio della vita” (The Breath of Life) oil on canvas 68” x 102”.

Image 4 
Her in 4000K LED 💡 in all her splendour ❤️.

Image 5 
Her new home: Lido Isle, Newport Beach. Image 5 (video) Lido Isle is a planned community of 800 beautiful custom homes, 250 of which are on the water.
 
Image 6 (video)
The exact day and waters (Ionian Sea) that inspired this painting. The coast of Salento, Italy.
 
Image 7 (video)
I hesitated sharing this because it’s so personal however, it is REALITY. This is only a fragment of the emotion that went into this painting, along with some really happy moments as well. It was a challenging year for me, I had just lost my grandmother and I also let go of several relationships that no longer served my highest good. I sacrificed a lot so that I could continue building my art career. I was learning to be my own best friend in a world that so often is cold and cut throat. I recorded the whole painting process of this painting and I found this video amongst the footage; it brought tears to my eyes again. We sometimes forget all that goes into an artist’s work, a part of you is infused into and recorded in all that you do and create. Something important to consider and remember. Artists… in your sensitivity there is power and there is presence, embrace it!
 
Image 8
When I was halfway there (half a year in, another half to go)! Sometimes the intuition you have to create something (that nobody else but you, can see) requires a whole lot of courage, especially with the difficulty or delay in achieving that vision. Can you relate with your own creative endeavours?
 
Images 9 & 10 
Arrivederci! Until we meet again 🙌🏻🌊

Have you ever wondered where an artist’s inspiration comes from? I know some of you are new to my profile so here’s a bit about my journey and my inspiration into painting water. 

More often than not, an artist’s inspiration is drawn from their life. Art is a reflection of the artist’s passions and personality and a reflection of their life experience, which is not always seen in the painting, however more often than not, it is felt. That I think, is why art can be so healing (for both the artist and the viewer) because something profound happens when we are vulnerable enough to express ourselves, an invisible thread connects the artist to the work and then the art to the viewer. I hope you never doubt your creativity, the value of it, and I hope as viewers we never forget that invisible thread… how it connects and can heal us all. 🌊✨

❤️CF @artistcarina

Last week it was an honour to speak at the Bernice Adams Legacy Awards Gala. This snippet from my speech includes the words I feel are most important to share with you here:
 
1. We all have a gift (or gifts) we can offer the world. More often than not, our gifts are the things that come most naturally to us. With our unique gifts I believe we are here to make this world a more beautiful place. Have you considered what your gifts are and how they could impact those closest to you, your community, the globe? 

2. Your art/artform is always the real reward. Although awards and recognition must be celebrated, try to remember that the real reward is your authentic expression of your gift. All else falls perfectly into place when the focus is on the true expression of your gifts. 
 
And finally, one of my favorite quotes: 

“The greatest danger for most of us is not that our aim is too high and we miss it, but that it is too low and we reach it.” - Michelangelo Buonarroti
 
Wherever you are in he world, have an inspiring weekend!

❤️ @artistcarina

Dear Artists (everyone), It takes a great deal of courage to have a vision and to bring it to fruition. If you need the approval of others to validate your inner vision or guidance then it is unlikely you will bring your vision to pass. Nothing is as challenging to sustain as the world and belief behind your eyes. You have to be strong enough to sustain a vision you cannot yet prove, strong enough to work at a pace that suits your soul, strong enough to focus and remove all distractions or adverse opinions, strong enough to go it alone, if you must. If you have an innate knowing to create or do something or to go somewhere then you must listen and follow that whisper.
 
Featured here is some insight into my new work. These paintings with the female figure are inspired by a vision I had several years ago. I later stumbled upon the photographs of Lucien Clerge; his work was urging me to begin this body of work that I’ve longed to create for so many years. For those of you who don’t know Lucien Clerge (1934 – 2014) or his work, swipe left to images 7-10 (UPDATE- I was forced to delete two of his images because of the nudity, but please go search his work involving the feminine nude in water, it’s truly beautiful)! He was a prominent photographer and long time friend of Pablo Picasso who he first officially met in 1955 in Cannes, France (last image - Lucien & Picasso).
 
This connection I have to water provoked the introduction of the female figure in water that you can now see in my work. Although these paintings depict the deep connection to water that I experience, they also speak of the link between water and woman: the strength, fragility, power, healing and life giving qualities that both woman and water possess. Water, afterall is what we are all made up of, and none of us would be here today without this natural resource. 

❤️ @artistcarina

🍁 Carina Francioso is an internationally acclaimed, award-winning Canadian artist hailing from Cambridge, Ontario.

🎓 As a child, Carina was passionate about art, excelling in high school art classes and eventually earning a 4-year Honours degree in Studio Specialization from the University of Waterloo.

🎨 With a family background rich in artists and musicians, it was only natural for Carina to embrace a creative career path.

🌊 Her current artwork is deeply influenced by her love for the world's seas and oceans. This passion stems from childhood summers spent on Georgian Bay and visits to Salento, Italy, where her father's family originates.

🏆 Carina's meticulous attention to detail has earned her numerous accolades such as the Arts & Culture Recognition Award from the city of Cambridge, the ARC/Arcadia Contemporary Gallery Award, the Toronto Outdoor Art Exhibition's Prime People's Choice Award, the Jocelyn Cowan Award, the Pencil & Paper Prize, and the 2018 Bernice Adams Memorial Visual Arts Award.

🌎 Her stunning work has graced the pages of various magazines like American Art Collector, GRAND Magazine, Art Renewal Center’s International Realism Salon Catalog, Hyperrealism Magazine, and Panoram Italia. Today, Carina's paintings can be found in private collections worldwide.

Presenting “Water is Life”, mixed media on wood board, 30” x 27”… a unique piece I created in support of and in collaboration with @charitywater . 

Charity: water @charitywater and their mission have been close to my ❤️ since the very beginning. Their vision is to end the world water crisis by bringing clean and safe water to people around the globe. My vision is to bring awareness to the vulnerability, protection and preservation of our world’s beautiful waters 🌊. Thus, this piece is born from a merging of these two visions…

The concept for this artwork was to use the yellow Jerry can as inspiration (the can is a primary tool used in every @charitywater project). So I decided to make Jerry my canvas and transform it into a work of art 🖼️! Thank you to @officialresinwonder for supplying me with the resin 🙏🏼.

This piece will be on exhibit and auctioned off at @theotherartfair in London, UK from Oct 12th-15th and 💯% of proceeds go towards future global @charitywater projects.

If you find yourself in London and would like to attend the exhibit, visit  www.theotherartfair.com/london/tickets/ and use code TOAFCW20 for 20% off your entry ticket.

Stay tuned for the auction link & details!

🌊CF

‘Water is Life,’ says fine artist @artistcarina through her submission for @theotherartfair. We couldn’t agree more. Known for her contemporary realist oil paintings that capture the beauty, power, and fragility of water, Carina depicted a vibrant scene on her jerry can-vas. 

“I love the saying ‘where your focus goes, energy flows,’” Carina shared, ‘so I make it my intention to focus on the positive, such as the beauty and life-force of water. Through my work, I hope to inspire others to become stewards of this natural resource.”

Carina’s work is on display at https://cwtr.org/3LYqFew (link in bio), along with a wide variety of other pieces you won’t want to miss! We’re so grateful for the time, talent, and effort that went into creating these truly stunning works of art.

A couple more shots of “Water is Life” for the @charitywater exhibit that happened a few weekends ago in London, UK at @theotherartfair . This piece has since SOLD 🔴.

Working on this project gifted me two things: 

1. It gave me more awareness into the hard truth that billions of people around the globe are still living with the daily challenge of accessing clean water sources.

2. It gave me hope knowing that organizations such as @charitywater are truly making a positive change in the 🌎. 

Grateful to have taken part, in my own small way, towards making an impact 🌊!

A couple weeks ago my dear friend and fellow artist Liana Carbone @lianamcarbone ( assisted by the talented @apizzanelli ) captured me in my element. Deepened by wider horizons, we shot these images under the gentle showers of the autumn rain🌧️.

As the year comes to a close, I find solace in my art. It becomes a mirror.
 
Reflecting on the journey I have taken throughout the year, each stroke of the brush represents a moment of growth, a challenge overcome, and a dream realized. The canvas becomes a tapestry of emotions, capturing the essence of the past twelve months.
 
As an artist who paints water, I am drawn to its fluidity and ever-changing form. Water is a symbol of life, representing the constant motion and adaptability that we all possess. Just as water flows through rivers and streams, we too navigate the twists and turns of life, embracing the unexpected and learning from each experience.
 
In my studio, surrounded by the tools of my trade, I am reminded of the power of creation. With each brushstroke, I breathe life onto the canvas, giving birth to a world of color, emotion and story telling.
 
This past year it was not just the water that captured my imagination; the feminine figure added depth and meaning to my art. Through the delicate curves and graceful lines, I aim to celebrate the strength and beauty of the feminine and her connection to water… a tribute to her resilience, her vulnerability, and her unwavering spirit. We all know HER.
 
Thank you 2023, Happy New Year 🎉!
